WEBVTT

00:00:16.465 --> 00:00:18.340
PHILIP GREENSPUN: So
remember, as VFR pilots,

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:20.890
you're actually going
to be doing stuff that

00:00:20.890 --> 00:00:26.500
is in some ways more challenging
than what airline pilots do,

00:00:26.500 --> 00:00:29.200
because you're always
trying to keep clearances

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:32.750
from clouds that the IFR
pilots don't care about.

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:34.990
And if you're flying a
low performance airplane,

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:40.150
you're also dealing with
flying through the weather

00:00:40.150 --> 00:00:42.290
instead of just
going on top of it.

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:46.690
So while you're
the VFR only pilot,

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:51.590
these non-local flights, really
pay attention to weather.

00:00:51.590 --> 00:00:55.502
Airspace, go and study this
a little bit before the exam.

00:00:55.502 --> 00:00:56.710
Here are the different kinds.

00:00:56.710 --> 00:00:58.070
Remember Class A is up high.

00:00:58.070 --> 00:00:59.770
You need an
instrument clearance.

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:02.260
Class B is around
the biggest airports.

00:01:02.260 --> 00:01:05.019
Class Charlie's around
Manchester, New Hampshire.

00:01:05.019 --> 00:01:07.330
And D is for Hanscom.

00:01:07.330 --> 00:01:09.910
And E is everywhere else.

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:11.740
OK.

00:01:11.740 --> 00:01:14.920
The goal for the basic
VFR weather minimums

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:19.360
is to make sure that an IFR
plane coming out of the cloud

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:22.240
has time to see and avoid
you, because the air traffic

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:26.200
controller's job is to separate
IFR airplanes from each other.

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:28.990
It's not to separate
IFR and VFR traffic.

00:01:28.990 --> 00:01:30.850
They will tell you about them.

00:01:30.850 --> 00:01:33.310
But you're responsible
as a VFR pilot

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:35.840
for staying reasonably
clear of clouds.

00:01:35.840 --> 00:01:39.130
So just review these
cloud clearances.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:46.450
Class E, you can see that
this is a pretty good one

00:01:46.450 --> 00:01:47.860
to remember for the test--

00:01:47.860 --> 00:01:53.620
500 below, 1,000 above,
2,000 horizontally.

00:01:53.620 --> 00:01:55.540
If you're really low
in Class G airspace,

00:01:55.540 --> 00:01:57.843
you can do some crazy stuff.

00:01:57.843 --> 00:01:59.760
Again, I don't think
that this is really there

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:03.970
to let you go from
Boston to Chicago scud

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:07.750
running with one
mile of visibility

00:02:07.750 --> 00:02:09.729
and just clear of the clouds.

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:12.790
I think it's more to enable
people to say, take off and do

00:02:12.790 --> 00:02:15.910
pattern work at
their home airport

00:02:15.910 --> 00:02:18.240
in some kind of little
tiny, very slow airplane.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.990
TINA SRIVASTAVA: Pattern
work is just what

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:21.407
we were drawing
on the chalkboard,

00:02:21.407 --> 00:02:23.530
flying the traffic
pattern at an airport.

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:24.760
PHILIP GREENSPUN: OK.

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:28.038
So again, yeah, just review the
presentation or the FAA book

00:02:28.038 --> 00:02:29.455
so you know your
weather minimums.

00:02:32.090 --> 00:02:34.433
Yeah, incredibly at
night for Class G,

00:02:34.433 --> 00:02:36.100
getting back to that
pattern work thing,

00:02:36.100 --> 00:02:38.620
if you want to go out and
practice takeoffs and landings

00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:41.440
at night, if you stay within
half a mile of the runway,

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:45.520
you can go right down to one
mile of visibility and right up

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:48.040
to the clouds.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:49.500
OK.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:51.630
Here's that chart again.

00:02:51.630 --> 00:02:52.130
Learn it.

00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:53.000
Know it.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:55.630
A special VFR-- actually
if you're at Hanscom

00:02:55.630 --> 00:03:00.400
